04740nam a22006975i 9780271079806DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20212017pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710798067 a10.1515/97802710798062doi  a(DE-B1597)584484  a(OCoLC)1262307487  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aART0151002bisacsh04a701/.852231 aKalba, Laura Anne, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aColor in the Age of Impressionism :bCommerce, Technology, and Art /cLaura Anne Kalba. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b108 color/11 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRefiguring Modernism ;v2200tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tChapter One. Michel- Eugène Chevreul, Color, and the Dangers of Excessive Variety -- tChapter Two . From Blue Roses to Yellow Violets: Flowers and the Cultivation of Color -- tChapter Three . Impressionism's Chemical Aesthetic: The Materials and Meanings of Color -- tChapter Four . Fireworks: Color, Fantasy, and the Visual Culture of Modern Enchantment -- tChapter Five . Chromolithography: Posters, Trade Cards, and the Politics of Ephemera Collecting in Fin-de-Siècle France -- tEpilogue . Autochromes and Neo- Impressionism: The End of the Age of Impressionism -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis study analyzes the impact of color-making technologies on the visual culture of nineteenth-century France, from the early commercialization of synthetic dyes to the Lumière brothers' perfection of the autochrome color photography process. Focusing on Impressionist art, Laura Anne Kalba examines the importance of dyes produced in the second half of the nineteenth century to the vision of artists such as Edgar Degas, Pierre-Auguste Renoir, and Claude Monet.The proliferation of vibrant new colors in France during this time challenged popular understandings of realism, abstraction, and fantasy in the realms of fine art and popular culture. More than simply adding a touch of spectacle to everyday life, Kalba shows, these bright, varied colors came to define the development of a consumer culture increasingly based on the sensual appeal of color. Impressionism-emerging at a time when inexpensively produced color functioned as one of the principal means by and through which people understood modes of visual perception and signification-mirrored and mediated this change, shaping the ways in which people made sense of both modern life and modern art.Demonstrating the central importance of color history and technologies to the study of visuality, Color in the Age of Impressionism adds a dynamic new layer to our understanding of visual and material culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aColor in art. 0aColorxSocial aspectsxHistoryx19th centuryxFrance. 0aColorxSocial aspectszFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aImpressionism (Art)xFrancexFrancexHistory. 0aImpressionism (Art)zFrance. 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311074523840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271079806zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271079806423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271079806.jpg  a978-3-11-074523-8  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-al